{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"79478a5ae6e4ab15edf597fec5626c05a9f3949cb94b260af631c830ccd043cb","slug":"medium-mixtures","location":"/explanation/medium_mixtures.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Medium Mixtures","content_includes_title":false,"github":"https://github.com/open223/docs.open223.info","numbering":{"title":{"offset":1}},"source_url":"https://github.com/open223/docs.open223.info/blob/main/explanation/medium_mixtures.md","edit_url":"https://github.com/open223/docs.open223.info/edit/main/explanation/medium_mixtures.md","thumbnail":"/build/mixed_medium-f0414318a00b2468f6ceb9008a1fc1ae.png","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"medium_mixtures.md","url":"/build/medium_mixtures-0f2eb52700bb076b62a286e6637dfb4e.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The 223 standard includes a large set of enumerations, defined as a hierarchy of subclasses under the class ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"ypAq4oQkwK"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:EnumerationKind","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"jgUtr1sS9m"},{"type":"text","value":".\nOne important piece of this hierarchy is the class ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"XMM8BVDWC8"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:EnumerationKind-Substance","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"NKrYSsGpv8"},{"type":"text","value":" and its direct subclass ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"oaLuE69Ksp"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:Substance-Medium","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"hCuVXQ6PVo"},{"type":"text","value":".\nIt is this branch of the hierarchy where you can find what you would expect to be flowing in a building, such as water, air and electricity. It is important to understand how a medium is modeled, especially when that medium is a mixture. The diagram below sketches the structure of the hierarchy. The names of the classes are abbreviated for clarity, so ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"oxB8Pj8qse"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:Substance-Medium","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"Sn9fN1i7ek"},{"type":"text","value":" is shown as Medium for example. In the standard, each of the names follows the hyphenated naming convention of <parent class>-<local class>.","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"U4EldMeE1D"}],"key":"jZboAhYcjz"},{"type":"image","url":"/build/mixed_medium-f0414318a00b2468f6ceb9008a1fc1ae.png","alt":"MixedMedium","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"ZzYbxYzhHT","urlSource":"images/mixed_medium.png"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note in the figure that there is a division of the Medium class into Mix and Constituent. The Mix class is further divided into Fluid and Power&Signal. Fluid means what you might think - a liquid or gas that typically flows inside some sort of conduit like a duct or a pipe. You can find Water and Air here. To capture the description of what is in a mixture, the model contains the class Constituent and its subclasses. These subclasses are intended to identify the constituents of a mixture. So, for example, a water-glycol mixture would be defined as ","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"ITtPJ2tvAL"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:Water-GlycolSolution","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"Sl96rpdEPp"},{"type":"text","value":", with two Properties via the relation ","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"olMQO2pcSD"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:composedOf","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"XyA7lj9yiU"},{"type":"text","value":". Each of these Properties has a relation ","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"Io4w7YuN94"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:ofConstituent","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"uVbOYauyoK"},{"type":"text","value":" that identifies one of the constituents from the Medium-Constituent hierarchy. Each Property also captures any other defining information. This is illustrated in the following figure for a 30%  Water-Glycol mixture.","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"aGLfKtTfaO"}],"key":"HX2kHCaErJ"},{"type":"image","url":"/build/glycol_example-c574e91566291460578bd35dac23bf7b.png","alt":"GlycolExample","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"X3R84LOINT","urlSource":"images/glycol_example.png"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Mixtures (","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"dbuhrqBmMC"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:Medium-Mix","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"kAR6dKvWm3"},{"type":"text","value":") and constituents (","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"n6XTBGTr0n"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:Medium-Constituent","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"mI5bK65r79"},{"type":"text","value":") are modeled this way to allow for compatibility validation among ConnectionPoints and Connections. Two mediums are deemed compatible if they share at least one common constituent.","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"PdMqcJL6LT"}],"key":"O36BU1nvri"}],"key":"nSVZGNQvwK"}],"key":"sFwkRYHJex"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Heat Transfer Equipment","url":"/heat-transfer-equipment","group":"Explanation"},"next":{"title":"Sensors and Properties","url":"/sensors-and-properties","group":"Explanation"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3000"}